The senate was nominally the source of authority in the government, but was continually overawed and overruled by the emperor when present; hence they were delighted with their present freedom from this restraint by the temporary absence of the new prince. How these few concluding sentences of the section disclose the feelings of the various classes of citizens at Rome towards the government of the coming emperor!

5. Miles urbanusl, “the city soldiery; '' as opposed to those in the provinces, and embracing the pretorian guard, the city co· horts, and perhaps the armed watchmen. Their long—continued allegiance to the Julian dynasty (Caesarum) rendered them reluctant to submit to the government of Galba, who was merely a soldier of. fortune, without any connection with the Caesars. Henceforth Caesar was merely an official name of the emperor, not a dynastic mma—donativum . . . promissum} This had been promised by Nymphidius, joint prefect of the pretorian guard with Tigellinus at the close of Nero’s reign, but was disowned by Galba. And in the three or four months which elapsed before the arrival of Galba in Rome, the pretorians had turned against him, and Nymphidius was even aspiring to secure the government for himself (imperium sibi molientis) ; in which attempt, however, he was crushed (oppres- sus).-praeventamque gratiamJ, “and that the place of favor (i.e. with the government) had been anticipated ; '' viz. by the legion which had made Galba emperor, and which accompanied him to Rome (i.e. the septima Galbiana, see 327). These circumstances, and certain personal peculiarities and sayings of Galba, here named, were all against him in the state of things which then existed. —nec enim . . . erantl, “nor indeed were other things according to this standard.'’ He was too straightforward and rigid for his times. ff
